  "metadata": {
    "type": "targeted_grid",
    "name": "user_weight_mini_test",
    "description": "4-scenario diagnostic test (2\u00d72 grid) for the user_custody_fraction implementation.\nQUESTION: Does the user null result (bias ratio 1.256 from User-PRIM) break when user nodes are assigned realistic cold-storage economic weight?\nDESIGN: - ucf=0.01 vs ucf=0.65: current negligible calibration vs realistic upper bound - split=0.50 vs split=0.70: neutral vs v27-leaning user population - Pool and econ parameters fixed at PRIM uncertainty zone midpoints - economic_split=0.60 (inversion zone \u2014 maximum sensitivity to new weight signals)\nINTERPRETATION: - If sweep_0000 and sweep_0001 give v26-wins (null holds at current calibration) and\n  sweep_0002/0003 give different outcomes: threshold found, proceed to Phase 1 full run.\n- If all four give identical outcomes: null appears robust, revisit Phase 1 priority. - Non-monotonic patterns (e.g., 0002=v26 but 0003=v27) are the most interesting finding.\nRUNTIME: 4 scenarios - 1 namespace: 2 scenarios sequential \u2192 ~7.2 hours (recommended: run sweep_0000,0001) - 2 namespaces: 4 scenarios, 2 per namespace \u2192 ~7.2 hours total\nGRID LAYOUT (user_custody_fraction \u00d7 user_split): - sweep_0000: ucf=0.01, split=0.50  \u2190 baseline, replicate prior null - sweep_0001: ucf=0.01, split=0.70  \u2190 baseline with v27-lean users - sweep_0002: ucf=0.65, split=0.50  \u2190 max weight, neutral user population - sweep_0003: ucf=0.65, split=0.70  \u2190 max weight, v27-leaning (most likely to break null)\n",
